      "usage": "The Ka was central to Egyptian funerary practices and concepts of existence. At birth, Khnum fashioned each person's Ka along with their body, infusing them with divine life force. Throughout life, the Ka remained inseparable from the person, representing their vitality and vigor. At death, the Ka separated but remained connected to the body - this is why mummification was essential, providing a preserved vessel for the Ka. Tombs were called 'houses of the Ka,' equipped with offerings tables for nourishment. Offering formulae invoked 'a thousand of bread, beer, oxen, and fowl' for the Ka. Tomb paintings showed the deceased receiving offerings, magically sustaining the Ka eternally. The Ka-priest (hem-ka) performed daily rituals to feed the deceased's Ka.",
